title: LEGCO QUESTION NO.17 (Written Reply)
question_text: Question: Will the Government inform this Council whether the Administration will consider introducing legislation to the effect that sellers are required to label clearly whether the meat on sale is chilled or fresh, so as to safeguard the interests of consumers; if so, of the details of the implementation plan; if not, the reasons for that?
reply_text:
Madam President, In the Provisional
Regional Council (ProRC) area, any chilled meat sold at licensed fresh provision shops are
required to be stored and displayed under refrigeration in accordance with the licensing
requirements of fresh provision shops. The tenants selling chilled meat in ProRC markets
are also required to follow such requirement. The Urban Services Department is at present
considering imposing similar requirements for the sale of chilled meat in the Provisional
Urban Council area. The above measures are
adequate for enabling consumers to identify whether the meat they purchase is fresh meat.

adequate for enabling consumers to identify whether the meat they purchase is fresh meat. We do not consider it necessary at present to introduce further legislative controls for this purpose.
